y the Second Empire. As hundreds of tenements were destroyed to make way for upscale apartment buildings, thousands of impoverished residents were forced to the periphery, which lacked the services enjoyed by wealthier parts of the city. Challenging the idea of Paris as the capital of modernity, da Costa Meyer shows how the city was the hub of a sprawling colonial empire extending from the Caribbean to Asia, and exposes the underlying violence that enriched it at the expense of overseas territories.This marvelously illustrated book brings to light the contributions of those who actually built and maintained the impressive infrastructure of Paris, and reveals the consequences of colonial practices for the city's cultural, economic, and political life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCity planningzFrancezParisxHistoryy19th century. 0aUrban renewalxSocial aspectszFrancezParis. 0aUrban renewalzFrancezParisxHistoryy19th century. 7aARCHITECTURE / Urban & Land Use Planning.2bisacsh  aAlgeria.  aAmateur.  aAmbivalence.  aAnnexation.  aApprenticeship.  aBanlieue.  aBetterment.  aBoulevard du Crime.  aBourgeoisie.  aBurial.  aCemetery.  aColor theory.  aCommodity.  aCreative work.  aCultivar.  aDepth of field.  aDiscrimination.  aEngraving.  aEthnic group.  aFaubourg.  aFertilizer.  aFontaine du Palmier.  aFortification.  aFrench colonial empire.  aFrench intervention in Mexico.  aGenerosity.  aGentrification.  aGeologist.  aGeorges-Eugène Haussmann.  aGeorges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de Buffon.  aGraphic arts.  aGustave Le Gray.  aGérard de Nerval.  aHarassment.  aHaussmann's renovation of Paris.  aHenri Lefebvre.  aHuman.  aHygiene.  aIdeology.  aIllegal immigration.  aImperial Ambitions.  aImperialism.  aInfrastructure.  aInsu